## 1. Frontmatter (YAML)

Frontmatter appears at the top of the file between `---` markers. It's parsed as YAML and becomes `markdoc.frontmatter`.

```yaml
---
title: "My Fancy Page"
description: "One-line summary."
layout: "docs"
tags:
  - tutorial
  - markdoc
published: true
date: 2025-10-29
authors:
  - name: "Shelton"
    twitter: "@shelton"
version: 1.2
---
```

Access in content via variables or functions: e.g. `$markdoc.frontmatter.title` or `{% markdoc.frontmatter.title %}` depending on render method.

---

## 2. Core Markdown nodes

Standard Markdown nodes are supported (CommonMark).

Examples:

```markdown
# H1
## H2
### H3

Paragraph text with **bold**, *italic*, and `inline code`.

- Unordered list
  - nested item
1. Ordered list

> Block quote

![Alt text](/assets/image.png "Optional title")
[Link text](https://example.com)
```

Markdoc preserves these nodes in the AST and allows annotations and tags to be mixed in.

---

## 3. Code fences and highlighting

Use fenced code blocks with language identifiers.

```js
console.log("Hello Markdoc");
```

You can also use the `{% code %}` tag (if present in your schema) to add extra rendering options.

```markdoc
{% code lang="js" filename="example.js" lineNumbers=true %}
console.log("hello");
{% /code %}
```

---

## 4. Comments

HTML-style comments are supported. They are removed during render (when `allowComments` is true).

```markdown
<!-- This comment will not appear in the rendered output -->
```

---

## 5. Tags — basic syntax

Tags are Markdoc’s structured components. Use `{% tagName attr="value" %}` for an opening tag and `{% /tagName %}` to close.

```markdoc
{% callout type="info" %}
This is an informational callout.
{% /callout %}
```

Tags can contain Markdown and nested tags.

---

## 6. Self-closing tags

If a tag doesn’t need a body, use the self-closing syntax `/%}`.

```markdoc
{% toc /%}
{% include src="./partials/sidebar.mdoc" /%}
```

---

## 7. Inline tags

Tags can be used inline within paragraphs for small components.

Example: embedding a badge or an inline code helper.

```markdoc
Use the {% badge text="beta" /%} release for testing.
```

Be aware: inline tags must render to inline elements (span-like) in your component implementation.

---

## 8. Tag attributes (types & examples)

Attributes can be strings, numbers, booleans, arrays, objects, variables, or expressions.

Examples:

```markdoc
{% widget
  name="weather"
  version=3
  enabled=true
  coords=[37.7749, -122.4194]
  meta={ id: "w-123", source: "api" }
  tags=["weather","api"]
  primaryColor=$theme.primary
/%}
```

<article>
This is nice
</article>

<footer>
This is nice
</footer>

- Strings — quoted or unquoted when simple: `name="x"` or `title=hello` (best to quote).
- Numbers — `count=5`
- Booleans — `visible=true`
- Arrays — `[1, 2, "three"]`
- Objects — `{ key: "value", n: 5 }`
- Variables — `$markdoc.frontmatter.title` or `$user.id`
- Expressions — `join(["a","b"], ", ")`

### Attribute precedence and evaluation

Attributes are evaluated at transform/render time. If they reference variables or functions, those must be present in the transform context or functions registry.

---

## 9. Annotations on nodes

Annotations let you attach attributes to native nodes (like headings, lists, table rows).

```markdoc
# My Heading {% id="my-heading" %}
- Item 1 {% class="muted" %}
```

Annotations are written following the node content and apply to that node. They are especially useful for controlling layout (e.g., column widths for table cells).

Example for tables:

```markdoc
{% table %}
* fooo {% width="25%" %}
___
* ok
{% /table %}
```

---

## 10. Variables and context

Markdoc supports variables accessible via `$` or templating in your render layer.

**Frontmatter variables:** `$markdoc.frontmatter.<key>`

**Custom variables:** you pass them through the transform/render call.

Example usage inside content:

```markdoc
Hello, {% $user.name %}!
Current version: {% $markdoc.frontmatter.version %}
```

Or using mustache-like interpolation (depending on renderer):

```markdown
{% $user.name %}
```

{% $22 %}
{% /22 %}
